Illusion Manifold Theory: A Mathematical Framework for Objective Meaning and Semantic Distortion

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

We introduce a mathematical theory of semantic distortion. Meaning is modeled as points on a Riemannian manifold, interpretation as maps that may contract, expand, or distort, and semantic illusion as a measurable divergence between true and perceived meaning. We prove convergence of multi‑agent interpretation to a fixed point under relaxed contractivity conditions, and extend the framework to stochastic dynamics, self‑correcting agents, and emergent manifolds in large language models. The theory uses Wasserstein geometry to quantify distortion and hyperbolic spaces to capture hierarchical structure. This work provides a purely mathematical foundation for studying meaning, distortion, and alignment.

---

1. Introduction

Language is a bridge between minds, but the bridge is never perfect. Existing theories focus on representing what meaning is; we instead formalize how meaning becomes distorted in interpretation. We treat meaning as a latent point on a Riemannian manifold, interpretation as a transformation, and distortion as a measurable divergence. The central claim is that under suitable conditions, multi‑agent interpretation converges to a fixed point—an objective meaning—and that agents can learn to reduce their own distortions.

The theory draws from differential geometry, dynamical systems, optimal transport, and information geometry. It is purely mathematical, with no empirical validation; the goal is to provide a rigorous framework for future applications.

---

2. Literature Review

We situate our work relative to:

· Philosophical semantics (Montague, Grice, Wittgenstein) – acknowledging that meaning is context‑dependent and co‑constructed, which motivates our use of multiple observers and context spaces.
· Distributional semantics (Landauer & Dumais, Mikolov et al.) – vector spaces of words; we extend to manifolds.
· Information geometry (Amari) – using Fisher metrics to structure statistical manifolds.
· Optimal transport (Villani) – Wasserstein distances as natural metrics on distributions.
· Dynamical systems in cognition (van Gelder, Hutchins) – fixed‑point attractors for beliefs.
· Hyperbolic embeddings (Nickel & Kiela, Tifrea et al.) – hierarchical concepts naturally embed in hyperbolic space.
· LLM geometry (Park et al., Saglam et al.) – recent work showing linear subspaces and layerwise structure; we incorporate these as constraints on the manifold.

The novel contribution is a unified geometric‑dynamical framework that quantifies distortion and proves convergence.

