4. Geometric and Dynamical Formulation

4.1 Interpretation Operator

For fixed C_i, B_i, we denote F_i: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} by F_i(M) = f_i(M, C_i, B_i). This is the interpretation operator of observer i.

4.2 Multi‑Agent Update

Given N observers, the collective interpretation is updated via the Fréchet mean of the perceived meanings:

M^{(t+1)} = \arg\min_{p \in \mathcal{M}} \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N d_g^2\bigl(p, F_i(M^{(t)})\bigr).
\]  

This is well‑defined when \mathcal{M} is a Hadamard manifold (or more generally geodesically convex and with bounded curvature; we will assume Hadamard to guarantee uniqueness). We denote this mapping by \mathcal{F}: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M}.

4.3 Euclidean Toy Model (for intuition)

If \mathcal{M} = \mathbb{R}^d with Euclidean metric and F_i(x) = A_i x + b_i with \|A_i\|_{\mathrm{op}} < 1, then

\mathcal{F}(x) = \bar{A}x + \bar{b},\quad \bar{A} = \frac{1}{N}\sum A_i,\ \bar{b} = \frac{1}{N}\sum b_i.
\]  

This affine map is a contraction (since \|\bar{A}\|_{\mathrm{op}} < 1), and its unique fixed point is x^* = (I-\bar{A})^{-1}\bar{b}. This example is used throughout to illustrate concepts.

