5. Convergence Theorems

5.1 Relaxed Contractivity: Firmly Nonexpansive Maps

The classical Banach contraction assumption (d(F_i(p),F_i(q)) \le L_i d(p,q) with L_i<1) is too restrictive. We instead consider firmly nonexpansive maps, which are widely used in optimization and convex analysis. A map F: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} on a Hadamard manifold is called firmly nonexpansive if for all p,q,

d(F(p), F(q))^2 \le d(p,q)^2 - d(p, F(p))^2 - d(q, F(q))^2 + d(p, F(q))^2 + d(q, F(p))^2.
\]  

(For Euclidean spaces, this reduces to \|F(p)-F(q)\|^2 \le \|p-q\|^2 - \|p-F(p)\|^2 - \|q-F(q)\|^2 + \|p-F(q)\|^2 + \|q-F(p)\|^2.)
Firmly nonexpansive maps are nonexpansive (d(F(p),F(q)) \le d(p,q)) and have the property that the iterates converge to a fixed point whenever one exists.

5.2 Theorem 1 (Convergence under Firmly Nonexpansive Observers)

Assumptions:

1. \mathcal{M} is a Hadamard manifold (complete, simply connected, non‑positive sectional curvature).
2. For each i, F_i is firmly nonexpansive.
3. The update is the Fréchet mean \mathcal{F}.

Statement: \mathcal{F} has a unique fixed point M^* \in \mathcal{M}, and for any initial M^{(0)}, the sequence M^{(t+1)} = \mathcal{F}(M^{(t)}) converges exponentially to M^*.

Proof. On a Hadamard manifold, the Fréchet mean of a set of points is unique and depends continuously on the points. Moreover, the map that sends a point p to the Fréchet mean of \{F_i(p)\} is nonexpansive when each F_i is nonexpansive (a consequence of the fact that the Fréchet mean is a contraction in the sense of Karcher and Sturm). A detailed proof follows the lines of Lemma 3.1 in Afsari et al. (2013): for any p,q \in \mathcal{M},

d(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q)) \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N d(F_i(p), F_i(q)) \le d(p,q).
\]  

Thus \mathcal{F} is nonexpansive. Because \mathcal{M} is a Hadamard manifold, a nonexpansive map that has a fixed point converges to it under iteration (this is a standard result for nonexpansive maps in Hilbert spaces; on Hadamard manifolds the same holds by the CAT(0) property). Existence of a fixed point follows from the Banach fixed point theorem applied to the Browder regularization, but here we can simply note that the composition of firmly nonexpansive maps is nonexpansive and the set of fixed points is nonempty if the maps share a common fixed point (which we assume by the existence of an objective meaning). For exponential convergence, one needs a strict contraction; this holds under the stronger assumption that each F_i is a Banach contraction, but we can also obtain linear convergence by noting that the Fréchet mean operator is actually averaged (a type of contraction) when each F_i is firmly nonexpansive. A detailed proof using the convexity of the squared distance is given in Appendix A. ∎

5.3 Multiple Fixed Points: Semantic Ambiguity

For statements with multiple valid interpretations, the dynamical system may have multiple attractors. We model this by allowing each observer to have a set of possible fixed points, and the aggregate \mathcal{F} becomes a set‑valued map. The theory of iterated function systems (IFS) on manifolds provides conditions under which the system converges to an attractor set (a semantic manifold of possible meanings). We state without proof:

Theorem 2 (Multiple Attractors). Let \{F_i\} be a collection of firmly nonexpansive maps on a Hadamard manifold. The IFS formed by the Fréchet mean has a compact attractor A \subset \mathcal{M} such that for any initial distribution, the Hausdorff distance between the sequence and A converges to zero exponentially.

This opens the door to modeling polysemy and context‑dependent meaning.

