6. Stochastic Dynamics

Real interpretation often involves randomness (e.g., sampling in LLMs). We model the update as a Markov chain on \mathcal{M} with transition kernel K(p,\cdot) defined by:

· Sample a random subset of observers (or random maps F_i) according to some distribution.
· Compute the Fréchet mean of their perceptions.

Theorem 3 (Wasserstein Contraction). Suppose the random maps satisfy \mathbb{E}[d(F_i(p),F_i(q))] \le L_i d(p,q) with L_i<1. Then the Markov chain has a unique stationary distribution \pi, and for any initial distribution \mu,

W_2(\mu_t, \pi) \le L_{\max}^t \, W_2(\mu_0, \pi),
\]  

where \mu_t is the distribution at time t.

Proof sketch. The Fréchet mean is a contraction in L^2‑Wasserstein distance (Anderes et al., 2016). Using the expectation bound, the transition kernel is a contraction in W_2. The result follows from standard results on Markov chains on metric spaces.

