7. Emergent Manifolds in Language Models

For large language models, there is no explicit encoding map \Phi. Instead, we consider the information geometry of the model’s predictive distribution. Let p_\theta(y \mid x) be an LLM’s conditional distribution over next tokens. The space of such distributions (indexed by contexts x) is a statistical manifold with Fisher metric. The emergent semantic manifold \mathcal{M} is defined as the image of the map x \mapsto p_\theta(\cdot \mid x), equipped with the Fisher metric. Recent work shows that for modern LLMs, this manifold is approximately linear (Park et al., 2024) or can be projected onto a low‑dimensional hyperbolic subspace for hierarchical concepts (Nickel & Kiela, 2017). The encoding map \Phi then becomes the map from a statement to its context embedding.

This perspective allows us to treat the LLM’s hidden states as points on \mathcal{M} and its internal processing as a composition of maps F_i (e.g., attention heads) that may be contractive or expansive. The theory applies directly, with the Fréchet mean replaced by the empirical mean in embedding space when the metric is Euclidean.

