9. Concrete Geometric Realizations

To make the theory concrete, we propose two canonical choices for \mathcal{M}.

9.1 Hyperbolic Geometry

Let \mathcal{M} = \mathbb{H}^d be the d‑dimensional hyperbolic space (e.g., the Poincaré ball model). The distance is

d_{\mathbb{H}}(x,y) = \operatorname{arcosh}\left(1 + 2\frac{\|x-y\|^2}{(1-\|x\|^2)(1-\|y\|^2)}\right).
\]  

Hyperbolic spaces naturally embed hierarchical concepts with low distortion. The Fréchet mean on \mathbb{H}^d is unique and can be computed iteratively (e.g., via gradient descent or a Karcher mean algorithm). However, there is no closed‑form solution, and the convergence analysis in Theorem 1 assumes the exact mean is computed at each step. In practice, approximation errors can be handled by standard results on inexact Fréchet means (see, e.g., Lou et al., 2020). All theorems hold with appropriate modifications (curvature -1).

9.2 Euclidean Subspace with Linear Representation Hypothesis

Recent empirical work (Park et al., 2024; Saglam et al., 2025) suggests that LLMs encode semantic information in low‑dimensional linear subspaces of the embedding space. In this case, \mathcal{M} is a Euclidean subspace \mathbb{R}^k \subset \mathbb{R}^D with standard metric. The Fréchet mean reduces to the arithmetic mean, and the distortion energy becomes the squared Euclidean distance between distributions (or W_2^2). This simplifies computations considerably and aligns with the linear representation hypothesis.

We treat both as valid specializations, leaving the choice to the application.

