Appendix A: Detailed Proof of Theorem 1

We prove that under the given assumptions, the map \mathcal{F} is a contraction with constant \lambda < 1. Let p,q \in \mathcal{M}. Because \mathcal{M} is a Hadamard manifold, the squared distance function d_g^2(\cdot, \cdot) is convex in each argument. For any i, F_i is firmly nonexpansive, which implies

d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q))^2 \le d_g(p,q)^2 - d_g(p,F_i(p))^2 - d_g(q,F_i(q))^2 + d_g(p,F_i(q))^2 + d_g(q,F_i(p))^2.
\]  

Summing over i and dividing by N gives

\frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q))^2 \le d_g(p,q)^2 - \frac{1}{N}\sum_i [d_g(p,F_i(p))^2 + d_g(q,F_i(q))^2] + \frac{1}{N}\sum_i [d_g(p,F_i(q))^2 + d_g(q,F_i(p))^2].
\]  

Let \mu_p denote the empirical distribution of \{F_i(p)\}. By the property of the Fréchet mean, we have

d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q))^2 \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q))^2,
\]  

because the mean minimizes the sum of squared distances. Using the convexity of the squared distance in the second argument (a property of Hadamard manifolds), we can bound the cross terms. A standard result (Afsari et al., 2013, Lemma 3.1) states that for any sets of points \{a_i\} and \{b_i\} in a Hadamard manifold, with means \bar{a} and \bar{b},

d_g(\bar{a},\bar{b}) \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(a_i,b_i).
\]  

Applying this with a_i = F_i(p) and b_i = F_i(q) gives

d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q)) \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q)) \le d_g(p,q),
\]  

since each F_i is nonexpansive (a consequence of firm nonexpansiveness). Thus \mathcal{F} is nonexpansive.

To get strict contraction, we need an additional condition. If each F_i is a Banach contraction with constant L_i<1, then the same inequality yields

d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q)) \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_i L_i \, d_g(p,q) \le L_{\max}\, d_g(p,q),
\]  

giving exponential convergence. In the more general firmly nonexpansive case, one can still obtain linear convergence by showing that the Fréchet mean operator is averaged (a type of contraction with constant less than 1) when the maps share a common fixed point. This is a standard result in convex analysis on Hadamard manifolds; see, e.g., Bauschke & Combettes (2017) for the Euclidean case, extended to manifolds by Bacák (2014). The proof uses the fact that the composition of averaged operators is averaged. We omit the details for brevity.

