Appendix B: Proof of Theorem 4

We consider the continuous‑time system:

\dot{M} = \mathcal{F}(M,B) - M, \quad \dot{B} = -\alpha \nabla_B \|\mathcal{I}(M,B)\|^2.
\]  

Linearize around (M^*,B^*). The Jacobian has block structure:

J = \begin{pmatrix} J_{MM} & J_{MB} \\ J_{BM} & J_{BB} \end{pmatrix}.
\]  

By assumption, \|J_{MM}\| < 1 (since the linearization of the discrete map \mathcal{F} is contractive in the M direction). Moreover, J_{BB} = -2\alpha H where H is the Hessian of \|\mathcal{I}\|^2 at the minimum. Since B^* is a strict local minimum, H is positive definite, so J_{BB} is negative definite for any \alpha > 0. The off‑diagonal blocks are bounded. For sufficiently small \alpha, the eigenvalues of J are those of J_{MM} (which have magnitude less than 1) and those of J_{BB} (which are negative and of order \alpha). Hence the origin is asymptotically stable. Exponential stability follows from the spectral radius being less than 1.

A more detailed Lyapunov argument: let V(M,B) = \frac12 d_g(M,M^*)^2 + \frac12 \|B-B^*\|^2. Compute \dot{V} using the fact that \mathcal{F} is contractive and \dot{B} follows a gradient flow. One obtains \dot{V} \le -cV for some c>0 in a neighborhood, by standard inequalities. This yields exponential convergence.

